t36.text: He napped whenever a nap-sized window appeared, with his scheduled lunch naps taken with his head resting on this little wooden thing I’d made for him when I was 13. It looked uncomfortable to all but him. He would always, always wake up naturally after exactly 29 minutes.pic.twitter.com/mNmzzCuPYP

t37.text: Born during the second great unpleasantness, he hated school and this was the only smile he could raise in all his years there. Great cowlick hairdo, too.pic.twitter.com/gNUpvrJXGE

t38.text: His old Holden ute. He was inordinately besotted with it and the only fight I ever heard of him being involved in came when a man sat on its bumper and refused to get off. Along came my sister in 1967 and and the old girl had to go.pic.twitter.com/r3GMj0mSsW

t39.text: He called this work. Nobody believed him. Dogs would stand up on the front seat with their paws on the dash, eager to get the first glimpse of their old friend. I once saw him sit on a concrete floor next to a terrified first timer for three hours to calm him down.pic.twitter.com/f4ik57xaNL
